children.Author: Quinn, 1957
children.Notes: Equus midlandensis was synonymized with Equus laurentius by Winans (1989) and Harris (1993). However, Scott et al. (2003) showed that the holotype specimen of Equus laurentius is a modern horse (Equus caballus), which renders Winans' (1989) "Equus laurentius species group" untenable. Scott et al. (2003) suggest that "some consideration" be given to the name Equus mexicanus for this group, but pending resolution of the Equus-Dinohippus synonymy, because if Dinohippus is included withn Equus, the separate taxon Dinohippus mexicanus then has priority. [ECG, 18 Jul 2007]

The traditional order Insectivora has been shown to be paraphyletic, and is now considered defunct (Wilson and Reeder 2005). The members of this order have been placed in three separate orders: Afrosoricida, Erinaceomorpha, and Soricomorpha. Erinaceomorpha contains the hedgehogs of Eurasia and Africa and the gymnures of southeast Asia. Afrosoricida contains the golden moles of southern Africa and the tenrecs of Madagascar and Africa. Most of the former Insectivora are assigned to Soricomorpha, including all North American species. [ECG, 11 Jul 2007]

children.Author: Leidy, 1852
children.Notes: Recent paleogenetic work (Shapiro et al. 2004) indicates that late Pleistocene (post Late Glacial Maximum) bison fall into two clades, a northern Beringian clade and a southern clade. The post-LGM southern clade is more closely related to Eurasian bison than to the contemporaneous east Beringian clade. Although they do not direct the taxonomic issues directly, the implication is that the northern clade is consistent with Bison priscus, whereas the southern clade is Bison bison, and any further taxonomic differentiation would be a the subspecies level. The late Pleistocene southern clade is comprised of the "short-horned" bison, B. "antiquus", B. "occidentalis", and B. bison bison. The genetic study did not address the earlier "long-horned" bison, B. latifrons (and allies), which may very well be an earlier member of a central North American phyletic lineage leading to B. bison. At this point, it seems sensible to recognize a Beringian taxon, B. priscus, a "long-horned" earlier southern taxon B. latifrons, and a "short-horned" later southern taxon "B. bison," with further differentiation at the subspecies level, which is generally consistent with Wilson (1974, 1978, 1996). The taxonomic status of Bison "priscus" south of the ice sheet remains uncertain. Shapiro et al. (2004) indicates gene flow between Beringia and central North America prior to LGM. An earlier B. "priscus" may be the common ancestor to both Bison bison and later Beringian B. priscus. [ECG, 3 Aug 2007]

children.Notes: Felis sp. is synonymized with Felidae sp. because the circumscription of Felis as understood by many past investigators would have included Felidae now separated into differnet genera, e.g. Lynx, Puma, etc. [E.C. Grimm, 12 Jun 2012]

children.Author: Tomida, 1987
children.Notes: Tomida (1987) described Pappogeomys (Cratogeomys) sansimonensis. However, molecular data indicate that Pappogeomys and  Cratogeomys are distinct monophyletic genera, albiet sister genera (see DeWalt et al. 1993. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 2:193-204; Hafner et al. 2009. Journal of Mammalogy 90:47-56). [E.C. Grimm, 18 Jun 2012]

children.Author: Gazin, 1942
children.Notes: Kurtén  and Anderson (1980) elevate Nerterogeomys to the genus level; however, recent treatments synonymize with Geomys (e.g. Patton 2005, McKenna and Bell 1997) or treat as a subgenus (e.g. Becker and White 1981, Martin et al. 2003b). Nerterogeomys is extinct.  [ECG, 19 Jul 2007]

children.Author: (Wilson, 1933)
children.Notes: Martin (1996) synonymized all living and fossil Ondatra under O. zibethicus and considers all fossil forms to form a phyletic sequence. Under his system O. idahoensis = O. zibethicus /idahoensis. [ECG, 2 Aug 2012]

children.Author: Wilson, 1933
children.Notes: Martin (1996) synonymized all living and fossil muskrats (Pliopotamys and Ondatra) under O. zibethicus and considers all fossil forms to form a phyletic sequence. Under his system Pliopotamys minor = Ondatra zibethicus /minor, the earliest chronomorph of this sequence. [ECG, 2 Aug 2012]

children.Author: Hibbard, 1937

children.Author: Meade, 1945

children.Author: (Gidley, 1926)
children.Notes: Cordillerion bensonensis is a nomen dubium (see Morgan & White, 2005). [E.C. Grimm, 15 Nov 2012]

children.Author: Hibbard, 1950
children.Notes: The synonymy of Bassariscus rexroadensis is apparently confused in the literature. Hibbard (1941, Am Midl Nat 26:337-368) named Procyon rexroadensis and later, based on another holotype, Bassariscus rexroadensis (1950, Contrib Mus Paleontol Univ Mich 8:113-192). These have sometimes been assumed to be synonyms; however, although B. rexroadensis is likely assignable to Procyon, the species assignment is uncertain (Bever, 2003, Southwestern Nat 48:249-256; Bjork, 1973, Trans Kansas Acad Sci 76:24-38). [E.C. Grimm, 27 Nov 2012]

children.Author: Martin, 1974
children.Notes: Martin (1974) named Pitymys aratai, which, here, is placed as Microtus (Pitymys) aratai follwoing the taxonimic placement of Pitymys by Musser & Carleton in Wilson & Reeder, eds.(2005). [E.C. Grimm, 4 Dec 2012]

children.Author: Günther, 1867
children.Notes: Traditionally the Lacertilia is recognized as a suborder of Squamata that includes the lizards. However, this group is paraphyletic because it excludes the snake subclade, and newer classifications no longer include the Lacertilia as a valid group. See Kumazawa (2007, Gene 388:19-26) and Fry et al. (2006, Naure:439:584-88). [E.C. Grimm, 18 Jan 2013]

children.Author: Matthew & Stirton, 1930|Linnaeus, 1758
children.Notes: Kurtén & Anderson (1980) consider this taxon at Cita Canyon to be Equus simplicidens.

children.Author: (C. Bauhini ex Linnaeus, 1753)
children.Notes: Linnaeus published Valeriana locusta in Species Plantarum 1:33–34. 1753. He listed as a synonym Valeriana campestris inodora major, published by Caspari Bauhini in Pinax Theatri botanici, p.165, 1623. As early as 1729, John Evelyn had referred this species to Valerianella in "Silva: or, a discourse of forest-trees...", as did Martín Sarmiento in "Catálogo de voces vulgares y en especial de voces gallegas de diferentes vegetables" in 1754-1755, and others. However, none of these satisfy the rules for valid publication, and the recombination Valerianella campestris does not appear to have been validly published. Linnaeus' Valeriana locusta has been validly recombined as Valerianella locusta. [E.C. Grimm, 2 Jul 2013]

children.Author: (Engelmann) Frić & Schelle ex Kreuzinger, 1935
children.Notes: Platyopuntia is often considered a subgenus of Opuntia including the prickly pear cacti. Flora of North America has elevated the subgenus Cylindropuntia to the genus level, with Opuntia now comprising only the former Platyopuntia. [E.C. Grimm, 8 Sep 2013]
